WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:03.363
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:07.190 --> 00:00:10.323
&gt;&gt; Letters About Literature
is a special project

00:00:11.430 --> 00:00:13.230
of the Center for the Book.

00:00:13.690 --> 00:00:15.090
It's about years old.

00:00:16.710 --> 00:00:17.293
I'm about to introduce Cathy
Gourley, who is the coordinator

00:00:20.060 --> 00:00:20.696
of the project and she'll
tell you a little bit

00:00:22.490 --> 00:00:26.690
about how today's project works
and then when we will meet three

00:00:27.810 --> 00:00:27.876
of the winners from the states.

00:00:29.810 --> 00:00:33.810
It's a project that from the
beginning has asked young people

00:00:34.460 --> 00:00:38.793
to write to authors about books
that have helped shape their lives

00:00:39.050 --> 00:00:42.850
or helped change the way that
they think about themselves.

00:00:42.970 --> 00:00:45.036
And the project had a beginning

00:00:45.060 --> 00:00:47.993
of around 18 years ago
with Cathy and myself.

00:00:48.860 --> 00:00:49.726
Cathy has been a consultation
for the Center

00:00:50.860 --> 00:00:52.726
for the Book for many years.

00:00:52.860 --> 00:00:52.916
And we started with Read
Magazine where Cathy was an editor

00:00:56.670 --> 00:01:00.870
and gradually as Cathy will
explain to you the nature of Letters

00:01:00.980 --> 00:01:05.246
About Literature has changed and
it's actually broadened in scope

00:01:05.710 --> 00:01:10.110
and Target has become our primary
sponsor, our major retail sponsor

00:01:11.460 --> 00:01:14.460
and that support has
enabled us to tie Letters

00:01:14.610 --> 00:01:17.076
About Literature to
the state centers.

00:01:17.180 --> 00:01:20.913
There are centers for the book
in every state and Letters

00:01:21.330 --> 00:01:25.263
About Literature is a project
that we not only offer to them

00:01:25.910 --> 00:01:29.776
with support from target but
also want them to encourage --

00:01:30.390 --> 00:01:32.523
encourage them to use as a basis

00:01:32.960 --> 00:01:35.826
for reading promotion
throughout the states.

00:01:36.190 --> 00:01:39.323
Many of you saw the state
centers who are really

00:01:39.490 --> 00:01:43.556
with the state libraries, dominate
our pavilion of the states.

00:01:43.730 --> 00:01:48.196
So this is an example of a project
that is truly national and is one

00:01:48.380 --> 00:01:52.313
of the projects that helps make
really the national testable

00:01:52.360 --> 00:01:52.380
of the book, something
that is truly national.

00:01:55.340 --> 00:01:55.343
And so I think it's appropriate
that we conclude this,

00:01:58.870 --> 00:01:59.073
the 10th anniversary of the
National Book Festival with hearing

00:02:02.800 --> 00:02:06.800
from the young people and delving
right into the heart of one

00:02:07.080 --> 00:02:09.013
of our most popular projects.

00:02:10.600 --> 00:02:13.466
I would Cathy Gourely
who is our coordinator

00:02:15.460 --> 00:02:15.810
to say a few words
about the project.

00:02:17.510 --> 00:02:17.566
And she can explain to you how
it's changed its educational tone.

00:02:21.720 --> 00:02:21.910
Then we will meet the families,
hear from the kids and also hear

00:02:25.730 --> 00:02:26.350
from the authors to whom two of
the letters were written this year.

00:02:29.510 --> 00:02:30.643
Cathy. [Applause]

00:02:31.510 --> 00:02:34.043
&gt;&gt; Cathy Gourely: Okay
you've got mail.

00:02:37.920 --> 00:02:40.053
That's an understatement for me.

00:02:40.890 --> 00:02:44.556
Each year in December the
post office delivers mail bins

00:02:46.810 --> 00:02:50.476
by the dozens filled with
letters and they come from all

00:02:51.930 --> 00:02:52.243
across the country and they
come from children as young as 9

00:02:55.550 --> 00:02:58.950
and 10 years old and seniors
in high school as well.

00:02:59.010 --> 00:03:01.410
And these letters are very personal.

00:03:03.190 --> 00:03:06.456
They're not writing to me,
but I get to read them.

00:03:07.220 --> 00:03:07.353
Letters About Literature started

00:03:09.220 --> 00:03:13.486
out as a program called Books
Changing Lives, but it kind evolved

00:03:14.370 --> 00:03:17.236
into a personal conversation
with an author.

00:03:17.850 --> 00:03:19.050
Here's what we do.

00:03:19.850 --> 00:03:23.783
We ask kids, we challenge kids,
write a letter to an author,

00:03:24.510 --> 00:03:26.376
living or dead, that's okay.

00:03:27.610 --> 00:03:31.676
Tell that author how his or her
work somehow changed your view

00:03:33.280 --> 00:03:35.013
of yourself or your world.

00:03:36.820 --> 00:03:39.153
We say, "Don't summarize the book."

00:03:39.750 --> 00:03:41.816
Why? The author wrote the book.

00:03:42.420 --> 00:03:45.220
So the author knows
what the book is about.

00:03:45.410 --> 00:03:49.143
What the author doesn't know
is how the book touched you.

00:03:49.870 --> 00:03:52.870
The author doesn't know
what emotions you felt

00:03:53.640 --> 00:03:54.376
when you were reading the book or
what thoughts entered your head

00:03:57.170 --> 00:03:59.570
after you finished reading the book.

00:04:00.080 --> 00:04:01.213
Write about that.

00:04:02.080 --> 00:04:03.080
Read the book.

00:04:04.080 --> 00:04:05.946
Get inspired and write back.

00:04:06.080 --> 00:04:06.480
Well, our kids do not disappoint us.

00:04:08.080 --> 00:04:10.480
This year we received
70,000 letters.

00:04:13.030 --> 00:04:13.216
In fact, I learned
new post office lingo.

00:04:15.510 --> 00:04:19.576
The mail bins came in a device
called an erk, which is as kind

00:04:20.150 --> 00:04:23.416
of big as a refrigerator
and it's filled up higher

00:04:24.710 --> 00:04:26.776
than my head with bins of mail.

00:04:27.960 --> 00:04:30.560
My team and I begin
to open the letters.

00:04:31.920 --> 00:04:32.920
We count them.

00:04:33.920 --> 00:04:34.010
We log them and then
we begin to read them.

00:04:36.630 --> 00:04:41.163
And we eliminated in the first two
rounds of reading, 63,000 letters.

00:04:41.960 --> 00:04:46.026
So only 7,000 letters nationally
advance to state competition,

00:04:49.100 --> 00:04:51.633
just to advance to
state is a big deal.

00:04:53.080 --> 00:04:54.480
So what happens next?

00:04:55.080 --> 00:04:58.613
Okay, so the state judges
now read their state letters

00:04:58.640 --> 00:04:59.040
and they choose their state winners.

00:05:00.640 --> 00:05:01.730
And we have three state
winners with you here today.

00:05:02.950 --> 00:05:06.483
So we've gone from 70,000
to about 7,000 to about 150.

00:05:08.990 --> 00:05:12.390
And then those letters go
on to national competition

00:05:13.490 --> 00:05:16.623
and the national winners,
we pick 6, that's all.

00:05:17.390 --> 00:05:21.856
So 70,000 to 7,000 to 150 to 6, and
we also pick 12 national honors.

00:05:24.310 --> 00:05:25.910
But here's the big deal.

00:05:26.310 --> 00:05:26.700
The national honors and the national
winners, they earn in addition

00:05:30.320 --> 00:05:34.786
to cash prizes, they earn a reading
promotion grant for the library.

00:05:36.810 --> 00:05:37.373
The 6 national winners each
earn 10,000 dollars for a school

00:05:40.180 --> 00:05:40.606
or a library, but they get
to nominate the school.

00:05:43.020 --> 00:05:46.953
And I'm just about done, but
in Anchorage this year, Alaska,

00:05:48.160 --> 00:05:51.226
they had their very first
ever national winner.

00:05:51.430 --> 00:05:53.430
She was junior in high school.

00:05:53.430 --> 00:05:57.830
And what she did was, she did not
nominate her high school library.

00:05:58.060 --> 00:06:02.660
She said to us, "I want to give this
money, 10,000 dollars to a school

00:06:03.560 --> 00:06:03.946
that needs it perhaps more
than my high school does."

00:06:06.640 --> 00:06:07.123
And she gave it to
an elementary school

00:06:08.690 --> 00:06:10.690
in Anchorage that was in need.

00:06:10.960 --> 00:06:13.293
And that principal didn't know her.

00:06:13.430 --> 00:06:15.430
The librarian didn't know her.

00:06:15.430 --> 00:06:16.563
So the kids know.

00:06:17.430 --> 00:06:18.430
They get it.

00:06:19.430 --> 00:06:21.296
And they're very altruistic.

00:06:21.580 --> 00:06:25.580
