00:10:41.190 --> 00:10:41.926
&gt;&gt; Olivia Marcantonio:
Dear Mr. Jerry Spinelli:

00:10:43.520 --> 00:10:43.720
Star Girl was one of those books.

00:10:45.520 --> 00:10:45.920
I don't know how else
to describe it.

00:10:47.520 --> 00:10:48.206
It is a book that completely
turns you inside out.

00:10:50.100 --> 00:10:51.366
Many books deal with a
character who is different,

00:10:52.100 --> 00:10:52.610
but none of those characters
actually enjoys being different.

00:10:55.590 --> 00:10:56.286
Star Girl showed me not to change,
to be my definition of normal,

00:10:59.160 --> 00:10:59.963
to be myself, as long as that self
does not have a negative effect

00:11:02.690 --> 00:11:03.756
on other people.

00:11:04.690 --> 00:11:06.223
This book surprised me.

00:11:06.690 --> 00:11:07.756
By reading it, I discovered
things about myself

00:11:08.690 --> 00:11:10.556
that I never noticed before.

00:11:10.690 --> 00:11:12.423
I discovered my strengths in
the characters of Star Girl.

00:11:12.690 --> 00:11:13.050
Like her, I don't pay attention
to negative peer pressure.

00:11:16.130 --> 00:11:16.666
I discovered my weaknesses
in Hillary's character.

00:11:18.860 --> 00:11:21.993
I am often determined to
dislike certain people.

00:11:22.100 --> 00:11:23.103
You should care about what other
people think of you, but not as much

00:11:25.630 --> 00:11:25.756
as you should care how you
make other people feel.

00:11:28.770 --> 00:11:30.053
We are the main character in our
own story, but it never occurs to us

00:11:32.020 --> 00:11:32.366
that we might be the bad
guy in someone else's.

00:11:34.740 --> 00:11:34.886
By reading Star Girl I stopped
seeing everyone else as "Them",

00:11:38.660 --> 00:11:38.803
with a capital "T" and started
seeing people as individuals.

00:11:42.450 --> 00:11:43.670
While everyone is made from
the same primary colors,

00:11:44.630 --> 00:11:46.496
it's how we mix those colors

00:11:46.630 --> 00:11:47.496
to create ourselves
that makes us different.

00:11:48.630 --> 00:11:49.866
Now I fully recognize that you
can't treat everyone the same way.

00:11:51.660 --> 00:11:53.326
What resolves an argument

00:11:53.660 --> 00:11:55.593
in one person may insight an
argument in a different person.

00:11:55.660 --> 00:11:57.326
I never knew that before.

00:11:58.310 --> 00:11:59.063
I have learned to accept other's
differences by reading Star Girl.

00:12:01.890 --> 00:12:02.280
Not necessarily big differences,
not even important differences.

00:12:05.700 --> 00:12:06.566
It could be something as
small and inconsequential

00:12:08.100 --> 00:12:08.110
as liking a book series
that I happen to hate.

00:12:11.090 --> 00:12:11.206
Then again a person might
dislike me because of that.

00:12:14.440 --> 00:12:16.573
I've learned to accept that too.

00:12:16.610 --> 00:12:17.726
I have learned to tolerate
people when the opinion

00:12:18.760 --> 00:12:18.883
of everyone else strongly
contradicts my own.

00:12:21.570 --> 00:12:22.203
Mr. Spinelli, before I read
Star Girl I was the same kind

00:12:24.670 --> 00:12:26.470
of different that I am now.

00:12:26.670 --> 00:12:26.980
I always speak my opinion,
good or bad, hurtful or not.

00:12:29.960 --> 00:12:30.826
Now though, you and
Star Girl have taught me

00:12:31.960 --> 00:12:33.770
that while being different is
good, I have to keep it in control

00:12:34.350 --> 00:12:35.020
like a bush, in some places you let
it grow and in others you prune it

00:12:38.280 --> 00:12:38.353
down so it doesn't stick out into
the neighbor's yard and annoy them.

00:12:42.740 --> 00:12:43.816
Mr. Spinelli, you taught me how
to be normal without changing,

00:12:45.730 --> 00:12:46.656
to change my image while the
way I think stays the same,

00:12:48.470 --> 00:12:48.870
to be myself without hurting others.

00:12:50.470 --> 00:12:51.470
Thank you.

