00:19:46.600 --> 00:19:47.933
&gt;&gt; Katherine Ann VanKirk:
Dear Mr. Michael Buckley:

00:19:48.600 --> 00:19:49.556
I would like to tell you about how
your series The Sisters Grimm helped

00:19:52.310 --> 00:19:52.323
me, but first I think you should
know a little bit about me.

00:19:56.230 --> 00:19:57.963
I am 12 years old, now 13.

00:19:58.740 --> 00:20:01.073
[Laughter] My parents are divorced.

00:20:01.320 --> 00:20:02.756
When you think about a divorce
you picture two people fighting

00:20:03.950 --> 00:20:04.083
and then them getting separated.

00:20:05.950 --> 00:20:07.883
Then everything becomes fine.

00:20:07.950 --> 00:20:09.283
This is not reality.

00:20:09.950 --> 00:20:11.150
I am part of a Lunch Bunch
group that is designed

00:20:11.950 --> 00:20:12.283
to help kids with problems at home.

00:20:13.950 --> 00:20:15.453
I'm the only kid there with divorced
parents and I'm not the only kid

00:20:16.980 --> 00:20:17.540
in the group that has
separated parents.

00:20:19.020 --> 00:20:19.326
This reality makes me feel even
worse about what happens at home.

00:20:22.980 --> 00:20:25.980
Amongst all this is my
little sister Caroline.

00:20:26.140 --> 00:20:26.880
I don't have a great
relationship with my sister.

00:20:28.600 --> 00:20:29.000
I mean its okay but
it's not the kind

00:20:30.600 --> 00:20:33.200
of relationship I would
have wished for.

00:20:33.300 --> 00:20:34.600
Now that you know a bit about
me, I would like to tell you

00:20:35.800 --> 00:20:35.936
about how I started reading books.

00:20:37.930 --> 00:20:38.950
The first time I read your
book was in the spring

00:20:40.110 --> 00:20:42.376
of 5th grade, about two years ago.

00:20:42.550 --> 00:20:45.950
I finished a book and I was
looking for another one.

00:20:46.390 --> 00:20:47.740
I asked my librarian and she gave me
your fourth book, Once Upon a Curse.

00:20:49.840 --> 00:20:52.306
I had no idea that
it was in a series.

00:20:52.880 --> 00:20:53.036
Of course, I had a few
questions, but I dropped them.

00:20:56.190 --> 00:21:00.590
One early Wednesday morning, I was
in SSR, Sustained Silent Reading

00:21:00.770 --> 00:21:01.770
and I found that I didn't
have a book to read.

00:21:02.770 --> 00:21:03.883
So I decided to look on the cart of
books that was there for us to read.

00:21:06.390 --> 00:21:10.790
And I found the first book in the
series, The Fairytale Detectives.

00:21:11.550 --> 00:21:14.750
I was surprised because
I had absolutely no idea.

00:21:15.070 --> 00:21:15.270
Anyway I checked it out and read it.

00:21:17.270 --> 00:21:17.873
It was just as good the
fourth book had been.

00:21:19.600 --> 00:21:23.000
I continued to read books
two, three and four again.

00:21:24.030 --> 00:21:24.383
Before school one morning
I went to see

00:21:26.210 --> 00:21:26.633
if they had book number
five and they didn't.

00:21:28.720 --> 00:21:29.166
I continued to look for it,
but I just couldn't find it.

00:21:31.940 --> 00:21:32.940


00:21:32.950 --> 00:21:34.086
While I was trying to find the
fifth book, I began to think

00:21:35.680 --> 00:21:35.863
about the characters in the series.

00:21:37.830 --> 00:21:38.383
I thought about how the
two sisters get along

00:21:40.210 --> 00:21:40.463
and have a blast without
their parents.

00:21:42.490 --> 00:21:42.943
I realized that these sisters
had a strong enough bond

00:21:45.570 --> 00:21:48.770
that it didn't make too
bad of an impact on them.

00:21:48.970 --> 00:21:49.000
I also began to think about this
could be similar in my life.

00:21:52.940 --> 00:21:53.806
If I had a better relationship
with my sister we could work

00:21:55.940 --> 00:21:57.193
through what happens and I
wouldn't have to hold it in until

00:21:58.620 --> 00:22:00.620
that once a month Lunch Bunch.

00:22:00.970 --> 00:22:02.770
I knew what I wanted to do.

00:22:02.970 --> 00:22:03.966
I wanted to make the relationship
I had with my sister better.

00:22:06.040 --> 00:22:08.573
The only problem was
how would I do it?

00:22:10.440 --> 00:22:10.790
I began to brainstorm some ideas
of how I could accomplish this.

00:22:14.290 --> 00:22:14.910
I noted that Sabrina and Daphne
spend a lot of time together.

00:22:17.670 --> 00:22:18.070
Caroline and I spent time together,
but nearly as much as they did.

00:22:21.670 --> 00:22:24.136
I decided to spend
more time with her.

00:22:24.660 --> 00:22:25.243
After about two weeks had
past I began to notice

00:22:27.210 --> 00:22:27.783
that we were treating
each other differently.

00:22:29.570 --> 00:22:29.926
As time went by we
got closer and closer.

00:22:31.880 --> 00:22:32.036
It was great, but problems
still came up.

00:22:34.390 --> 00:22:34.813
There was no way we could prevent
this but we talked everything

00:22:38.100 --> 00:22:39.766
at SM's, secret meetings.

00:22:40.410 --> 00:22:41.083
During an SM we would talk
about what was bothering us

00:22:43.270 --> 00:22:45.536
and what we would do to change it.

00:22:45.700 --> 00:22:46.323
These meetings were like
my Lunch Bunch meetings

00:22:48.210 --> 00:22:48.346
but they were private
and overall better.

00:22:50.740 --> 00:22:51.943
Now I feel like I could get
through anything with my sister.

00:22:53.470 --> 00:22:53.906
I never dreamed of having
a relationship this strong.

00:22:56.500 --> 00:22:57.146
I want to thank you for
writing this series.

00:22:58.720 --> 00:22:59.490
One thing, which I think you'll
happy to hear is that last weekend,

00:23:02.350 --> 00:23:06.883
well not last weekend but you know,
I found book number five and six.

00:23:07.460 --> 00:23:09.660
Sincerely, Katherine Ann Vankirk.

00:23:09.960 --> 00:23:10.960
[Applause]

00:23:18.890 --> 00:23:18.970
&gt;&gt; John: You want to go first.

00:23:20.810 --> 00:23:24.610
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: I asked
John Ko to give me a minute

00:23:25.980 --> 00:23:30.113
because I think all of us were
deeply moved by Claire's letter.

00:23:30.580 --> 00:23:30.666
And I didn't have Jerry
Spinelli's advantage

00:23:33.360 --> 00:23:35.160
of seeing the letter first.

00:23:35.360 --> 00:23:37.293
I heard it when you heard it.

00:23:37.360 --> 00:23:40.960
I think the thing that struck
me in your letter Claire,

00:23:41.970 --> 00:23:44.103
was how important friendship is.

00:23:45.340 --> 00:23:45.430
And I know in my life I've
had to move many times

00:23:48.450 --> 00:23:50.316
and have left behind friends

00:23:50.450 --> 00:23:50.933
that I thought I could
not bear to live without.

00:23:53.100 --> 00:23:56.700
And I've lost friends who
have died, and at my age more

00:23:58.190 --> 00:24:00.390
and more of my friends are dying.

00:24:01.960 --> 00:24:04.693
And I think what I've
learned through that

00:24:05.480 --> 00:24:05.546
and I think what you've learned

00:24:07.480 --> 00:24:07.700
through that is how
precious friendship is.

00:24:10.060 --> 00:24:14.593
And that the fact that we've had
those wonderful friendships makes it

00:24:15.140 --> 00:24:15.376
possible for us to reach
out to other people in a way

00:24:18.370 --> 00:24:21.503
that we couldn't have
without those friendships.

00:24:23.090 --> 00:24:23.746
And I'm very grateful that
that's what you learned

00:24:25.700 --> 00:24:25.746
from reading Bridge to Terabithia.

00:24:27.920 --> 00:24:28.920
You know I always say that the
writer doesn't have a right

00:24:30.720 --> 00:24:30.906
to tell the reader what
to take from a book.

00:24:33.400 --> 00:24:35.800
And your teacher doesn't
have a right

00:24:36.580 --> 00:24:36.970
to tell you what to
take from a book.

00:24:38.590 --> 00:24:42.790
No one has a right to tell you
what the book should mean to you.

00:24:43.610 --> 00:24:47.276
But it makes me very happy
to know that what you learned

00:24:50.200 --> 00:24:50.233
from that book is how
precious friendship was

00:24:53.100 --> 00:24:56.233
and that you could never
turn your back on that.

00:24:56.310 --> 00:24:58.576
So thanks so much for your letter.

00:25:09.390 --> 00:25:10.390
[Applause]

00:25:11.390 --> 00:25:15.856
&gt;&gt; Michael Buckley: Katherine I am
a little choked up by your letter

00:25:16.370 --> 00:25:18.770
and that's not good
because I'm 6' 3"

00:25:19.180 --> 00:25:21.580
and people laugh at
you when you cry.

00:25:22.140 --> 00:25:25.006
[Laughter] One of the
things I set out to do

00:25:26.020 --> 00:25:30.286
with The Sisters Grimm was tell
a very simple message and that is

00:25:31.020 --> 00:25:34.820
that the real magic in the
world doesn't come from wizards

00:25:35.940 --> 00:25:38.406
and magic wands, it
comes from family.

00:25:39.350 --> 00:25:42.616
And of all the people who
have written me letters,

00:25:43.600 --> 00:25:45.600
you seem to get that the best.

00:25:46.950 --> 00:25:51.483
I'm glad that the book has had a
positive impact on your relationship

00:25:51.910 --> 00:25:56.576
with your sister and hopefully you
can carry that into your adult life.

00:25:56.640 --> 00:26:00.306
Because as you get older
you'll hear time and time again

00:26:02.010 --> 00:26:06.143
that you can pick your friends
but you cannot pick your family.

00:26:06.240 --> 00:26:08.440
But the true magic of a family is

00:26:10.770 --> 00:26:11.200
that everyone is a
little bit different,

00:26:12.940 --> 00:26:16.406
but they all come together
to form one amazing group.

00:26:16.880 --> 00:26:19.080
I'm very happy that you get that.

00:26:20.000 --> 00:26:23.600
The one thing I would like
to say is I get many letters

00:26:24.900 --> 00:26:26.900
from kids who enjoy the books.

00:26:28.160 --> 00:26:32.693
I never thought that anybody would
even read my book when I wrote it,

00:26:32.820 --> 00:26:35.220
let alone write me
a letter about it.

00:26:35.940 --> 00:26:38.006
And it's truly a special treat.

00:26:40.710 --> 00:26:41.883
I think that when a writer sits
down, well at least some of us,

00:26:43.670 --> 00:26:44.203
when we sit down we
dream that we're going

00:26:45.870 --> 00:26:46.126
to write the next Harry Potter, the
next Wimpy Kid and we're just going

00:26:50.280 --> 00:26:53.146
to be swimming in money
like Scrooge McDuck.

00:26:53.950 --> 00:26:54.950


00:26:55.720 --> 00:26:59.320
[Laughter] But as you go on
in your career as a writer,

00:27:00.860 --> 00:27:05.060
at least what I've come across
is that the real treasures to me,

00:27:05.970 --> 00:27:09.503
the real reward of what I
do is fans like you who seem

00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:13.533
to understand me even better
than I understand myself.

00:27:15.920 --> 00:27:19.920
So thank you so much for putting
such time and effort into it

00:27:20.260 --> 00:27:24.460
and I truly hope that your sister
has stopped being such a jerk.

00:27:25.930 --> 00:27:27.330
